{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565423"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:26:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:26:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17496"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17496"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.74,0.03,0.08,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10186"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70969"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10186"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17496"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56438"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11179"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11949"},{"type":"tags","id":"12207"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23846"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43694"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70969"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her routine antenatal visit at 12 weeks gestation. This is her first pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy supplements. She appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA dating ultrasound scan reveals a single live fetus with crown-rump length consistent with dates. The cranial vault appears absent with only the brainstem and cerebellum visible, giving a characteristic \u0027Mickey Mouse\u0027 appearance in the coronal view. The remainder of the fetal anatomy appears normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Encephalocele","Anencephaly","Hydranencephaly","Holoprosencephaly","Acrania"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ultrasound findings described are pathognomonic for anencephaly, which is characterised by the absence of the cranial vault and cerebral hemispheres. The \u0027Mickey Mouse sign\u0027 refers to the appearance of the preserved brainstem and cerebellum without the overlying cerebral tissue, visible on coronal views in early pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnencephaly\u003C/strong\u003E is a lethal neural tube defect that occurs when the rostral (head) end of the neural tube fails to close during early embryonic development. It is typically diagnosed in the first trimester and is incompatible with life. The condition is associated with elevated maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHoloprosencephaly\u003C/strong\u003E is a different developmental abnormality where the prosencephalon (forebrain) fails to divide into two cerebral hemispheres. While severe, it typically shows some degree of cranial vault formation, unlike in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEncephalocele\u003C/strong\u003E represents a herniation of brain tissue through a defect in the skull. The cranial vault would still be largely present, with a focal defect, unlike the complete absence seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcrania\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the absence of the skull vault but with the presence of brain tissue. While related to anencephaly, it represents an earlier stage in the same pathological process before the exposed neural tissue degenerates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydranencephaly\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by the replacement of the cerebral hemispheres with cerebrospinal fluid-filled spaces, but the cranial vault is typically present and normal in size.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anencephaly is characterised by absence of the cranial vault and cerebral hemispheres on ultrasound.","The \u0027Mickey Mouse sign\u0027 on early pregnancy ultrasound represents absent forebrain with preserved brainstem and cerebellum.","First trimester screening can detect up to 100% of cases of anencephaly."],"references":["Johnson SP, Sebire NJ, Snijders RJ, Tunkel S, Nicolaides KH. Ultrasound screening for anencephaly at 10-14 weeks of gestation. Ultrasound Obstet Gynecol. 1997 Jan;9(1):14-6. doi: 10.1046/j.1469-0705.1997.09010014.x. PMID: 9060123.","Cook RJ, Erdman JN, Hevia M, Dickens BM. Prenatal management of anencephaly. Int J Gynaecol Obstet. 2008 Sep;102(3):304-8. doi: 10.1016/j.ijgo.2008.05.002. Epub 2008 Jul 7. PMID: 18603246."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56438"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17496"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56438"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T17:28:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T17:30:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10186"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70969"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null